# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: esd-protection
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] ESD can create spectacular electric sparks (lightning, with the accompanying sound of thunder, is an example of a large-scale ESD event), but also less dramatic forms, which may be neither seen nor heard, yet still be large enough to cause damage to sensitive electronic devices.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Electric sparks require a field strength above approximately 4 million V/m in air, as notably occurs in lightning strikes.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Similar forms of electric discharge include corona discharge from sharp electrodes, brush discharge from blunt electrodes, etc.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] ESD can cause harmful effects of importance in industry, including explosions in gas, fuel vapor and coal dust, as well as failure of solid state electronics components such as integrated circuits.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] These can suffer permanent damage when subjected to high voltages.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Electronics manufacturers therefore establish electrostatic protective areas free of static, using measures to prevent charging, such as avoiding highly charging materials and measures to remove static such as grounding human workers, providing antistatic devices, and controlling humidity.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] ESD simulators may be used to test electronic devices, for example with a human body model or a charged device model.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] One of the causes of ESD events is static electricity.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Static electricity is often generated through tribocharging, the separation of electric charges that occurs when two materials are brought into contact and then separated.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Examples of tribocharging include walking on a rug, rubbing a plastic comb against dry hair, rubbing a balloon against a sweater, ascending from a fabric car seat, or removing some types of plastic packaging.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] In all these cases, the breaking of contact between two materials results in tribocharging, thus creating a difference of electrical potential that can lead to an ESD event.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Another cause of ESD damage is through electrostatic induction.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] This occurs when an electrically charged object is placed near a conductive object isolated from the ground.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] The presence of the charged object creates an electrostatic field that causes electrical charges on the surface of the other object to redistribute.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Even though the net electrostatic charge of the object has not changed, it now has regions of excess positive and negative charges.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] An ESD event may occur when the object comes into contact with a conductive path.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] For example, charged regions on the surfaces of styrofoam cups or bags can induce potential on nearby ESD sensitive components via electrostatic induction and an ESD event may occur if the component is touched with a metallic tool.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] ESD can also be caused by energetic charged particles impinging on an object.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] This causes increasing surface and deep charging.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] This is a known hazard for most spacecraft.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Electrostatic discharge (ESD) phenomena vary in complexity and magnitude, with the electric spark being the most visible and dramatic example.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] This occurs when a strong electric field ionizes the air, creating a conductive channel that can convey an electric current.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] People may experience this as a small jolt of discomfort, but ESD can inflict severe damage on electronic components, potentially leading to malfunctions and failures.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] In hazardous environments where flammable gases or dust particles are present, ESD can trigger fires or explosions.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Not all ESD events, however, are accompanied by a visible spark or noise.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] It is possible for a person to carry a charge that, while undetectable to the human senses, can still be potent enough to harm delicate electronics.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Some components can be compromised by discharges as faint as 30 V, with such damage sometimes not becoming apparent until significant usage has occurred, thus affecting the lifespan and performance of the devices.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Cable discharge events (CDEs) are discharges occurring when connecting electrical cables to a device.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] A spark is triggered when the electric field strength exceeds approximately 4–30 kV/cm—the dielectric field strength of air.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] This may cause a very rapid increase in the number of free electrons and ions in the air, temporarily causing the air to abruptly become an electrical conductor in a process called dielectric breakdown.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Perhaps the best known example of a natural spark is lightning.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] In this case the electric potential between a cloud and ground, or between two clouds, is typically hundreds of millions of volts.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] The resulting current that cycles through the stroke channel causes an enormous transfer of energy.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] On a much smaller scale, sparks can form in air during electrostatic discharges from charged objects that are charged to as little as 380 V (Paschen's law).
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Earth's atmosphere consists of 21% oxygen (O2) and 78% nitrogen (N2).
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] During an electrostatic discharge, such as a lightning flash, the affected atmospheric molecules become electrically overstressed.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] The diatomic oxygen molecules are split, and then recombine to form ozone (O3), which is unstable, or reacts with metals and organic matter.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] If the electrical stress is high enough, nitrogen oxides (NOx) can form.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Both products are toxic to animals, and nitrogen oxides are essential for nitrogen fixation.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Ozone attacks all organic matter by ozonolysis and is used in water purification.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Sparks are an ignition source in combustible environments that may lead to catastrophic explosions in concentrated fuel environments.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Most explosions can be traced back to a tiny electrostatic discharge, whether it was an unexpected combustible fuel leak invading a known open air sparking device, or an unexpected spark in a known fuel rich environment.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] The result is the same if oxygen is present and the three criteria of the fire triangle have been combined.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Many electronic components, especially integrated circuits and microchips, can be damaged by ESD.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Sensitive components need to be protected during and after manufacture, during shipping and device assembly, and in the finished device.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Grounding is especially important for effective ESD control.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] It should be clearly defined, and regularly evaluated.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] In manufacturing, prevention of ESD is based on an Electrostatic Discharge Protected Area (EPA).
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] The EPA can be a small workstation or a large manufacturing area.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] The main principle of an EPA is that there are no highly-charging materials in the vicinity of ESD sensitive electronics, all conductive and dissipative materials are grounded, workers are grounded, and charge build-up on ESD sensitive electronics is prevented.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] International standards are used to define a typical EPA and can be found for example from International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) or American National Standards Institute (ANSI).
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Humid conditions prevent electrostatic charge generation because the thin layer of moisture that accumulates on most surfaces serves to dissipate electric charges.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Ionizers are used especially when insulative materials cannot be grounded.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Ionization systems help to neutralize charged surface regions on insulative or dielectric materials.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Insulating materials prone to triboelectric charging of more than 2,000 V should be kept away at least 12 inches from sensitive devices to prevent accidental charging of devices through field induction.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] On aircraft, static dischargers are used on the trailing edges of wings and other surfaces.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Manufacturers and users of integrated circuits must take precautions to avoid ESD.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] ESD prevention can be part of the device itself and include special design techniques for device input and output pins.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] External protection components can also be used with circuit layout.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Due to dielectric nature of electronics component and assemblies, electrostatic charging cannot be completely prevented during handling of devices.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Most of ESD sensitive electronic assemblies and components are also so small that manufacturing and handling is done with automated equipment.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] ESD prevention activities are therefore important with those processes where components come into direct contact with equipment surfaces.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] In addition, it is important to prevent ESD when an electrostatic discharge sensitive component is connected with other conductive parts of the product itself.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] An efficient way to prevent ESD is to use materials that are not too conductive but will slowly conduct static charges away.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] These materials are called static dissipative and have resistivity values below 1012 ohm-meters.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Materials in automated manufacturing which will touch on conductive areas of ESD sensitive electronic should be made of dissipative material, and the dissipative material must be grounded.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] These special materials are able to conduct electricity, but do so very slowly.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Any built-up static charges dissipate without the sudden discharge that can harm the internal structure of silicon circuits.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Sensitive devices need to be protected during shipping, handling, and storage.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] The buildup and discharge of static can be minimized by controlling the surface resistance and volume resistivity of packaging materials.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Packaging is also designed to minimize frictional or triboelectric charging of packs due to rubbing together during shipping, and it may be necessary to incorporate electrostatic or electromagnetic shielding in the packaging material.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] A common example is that semiconductor devices and computer components are usually shipped in an antistatic bag made of a partially conductive plastic, which acts as a Faraday cage to protect the contents against ESD.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] For testing the susceptibility of electronic devices to ESD from human contact, an ESD Simulator with a special output circuit, called the human body model (HBM) is often used.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] This consists of a capacitor in series with a resistor.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] The capacitor is charged to a specified high voltage from an external source, and then suddenly discharged through the resistor into an electrical terminal of the device under test.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] One of the most widely used models is defined in the JEDEC 22-A114-B standard, which specifies a 100 picofarad capacitor and a 1,500 ohm resistor.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Other similar standards are MIL-STD-883 Method 3015, and the ESD Association's ESD STM5.1.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] For compliance to European Union standards for Information Technology Equipment, the IEC/EN 61000-4-2 test specification is used.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Another specification referenced by equipment maker Schaffner calls for C = 150 pF and R = 330 Ω which provides high fidelity results.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] While the theory is mostly there, very few companies measure the real ESD survival rate.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Guidelines and requirements are given for test cell geometries, generator specifications, test levels, discharge rate and waveform, types and points of discharge on the "victim" product, and functional criteria for gauging product survivability.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] A charged device model (CDM) test is used to define the ESD a device can withstand when the device itself has an electrostatic charge and discharges due to metal contact.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] This discharge type is the most common type of ESD in electronic devices and causes most of the ESD damages in their manufacturing.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] CDM discharge depends mainly on parasitic parameters of the discharge and strongly depends on size and type of component package.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] One of the most widely used CDM simulation test models is defined by the JEDEC.
[src:esd-protection/electrostatic-discharge] Other standardized ESD test circuits include the machine model (MM) and transmission line pulse (TLP).
[src:esd-protection/human-body-model] The **human-body model** (**HBM**) is the most commonly used model for characterizing the susceptibility of an electronic device to damage from electrostatic discharge (ESD).
[src:esd-protection/human-body-model] The model is a simulation of the discharge which might occur when a human touches an electronic device.
[src:esd-protection/human-body-model] The HBM definition most widely used is the test model defined in the United States military standard, MIL-STD-883, Method 3015.9, Electrostatic Discharge Sensitivity Classification.
[src:esd-protection/human-body-model] This method establishes a simplified equivalent electrical circuit and the necessary test procedures required to model an HBM ESD event.
[src:esd-protection/human-body-model] An internationally widely used standard is JEDEC standard JS-001.
[src:esd-protection/human-body-model] HBM is used primarily for manufacturing environments to quantify an integrated circuit to survive the manufacturing process.
[src:esd-protection/human-body-model] A similar standard, IEC 61000-4-2, is used for system level testing and quantifies protection levels for a real world ESD event in an uncontrolled environment.
[src:esd-protection/human-body-model] In both JS-001-2012 and MIL-STD-883H the charged human body is modeled by a 100 pF capacitor and a 1500 ohm discharging resistance.
[src:esd-protection/human-body-model] During testing, the capacitor is fully charged to several kilovolts (2 kV, 4 kV, 6 kV and 8 kV are typical standard levels) and then discharged through the resistor connected in series to the device under test.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] An **ohmic contact** is a non-rectifying electrical junction: a junction between two conductors that has a linear current–voltage (I–V) curve as with Ohm's law.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Low-resistance ohmic contacts are used to allow charge to flow easily in both directions between the two conductors, without blocking due to rectification or excess power dissipation due to voltage thresholds.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] By contrast, a junction or contact that does not demonstrate a linear I–V curve is called non-ohmic.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Non-ohmic contacts come in a number of forms, such as p–n junction, Schottky barrier, rectifying heterojunction, or breakdown junction.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Generally the term "ohmic contact" implicitly refers to an ohmic contact of a metal to a semiconductor, where achieving ohmic contact resistance is possible but requires careful technique.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Stable contacts at semiconductor interfaces, with low contact resistance and linear I–V behavior, are critical for the performance and reliability of semiconductor devices, and their preparation and characterization are major efforts in circuit fabrication.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Poorly prepared junctions to semiconductors can easily show rectifying behaviour by causing depletion of the semiconductor near the junction, rendering the device useless by blocking the flow of charge between those devices and the external circuitry.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Ohmic contacts to semiconductors are typically constructed by depositing thin metal films of a carefully chosen composition, possibly followed by annealing to alter the semiconductor–metal bond.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Both ohmic contacts and Schottky barriers are dependent on the Schottky barrier height, which sets the threshold for the excess energy an electron requires to pass from the semiconductor to the metal.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] For the junction to admit electrons easily in both directions (ohmic contact), the barrier height must be small in at least some parts of the junction surface.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] To form an excellent ohmic contact (low resistance), the barrier height should be small everywhere and furthermore the interface should not reflect electrons.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] The Schottky barrier height between a metal and semiconductor is naively predicted by the Schottky–Mott rule to be proportional to the difference of the metal-vacuum work function and the semiconductor-vacuum electron affinity.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] In practice, most metal–semiconductor interfaces do not follow this rule to the predicted degree.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Instead, the chemical termination of the semiconductor crystal against a metal creates electron states within its band gap.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] The nature of these metal-induced gap states and their occupation by electrons tends to pin the center of the band gap to the Fermi level, an effect known as Fermi level pinning.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Thus, the heights of the Schottky barriers in metal–semiconductor contacts often show little dependence on the value of the semiconductor or metal work functions, in stark contrast to the Schottky–Mott rule.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Different semiconductors exhibit this Fermi level pinning to different degrees, but a technological consequence is that high quality (low resistance) ohmic contacts are usually difficult to form in important semiconductors such as silicon and gallium arsenide.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] The Schottky–Mott rule is not entirely incorrect since, in practice, metals with high work functions form the best contacts to p-type semiconductors, while those with low work functions form the best contacts to n-type semiconductors.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Unfortunately experiments have shown that the predictive power of the model doesn't extend much beyond this statement.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Under realistic conditions, contact metals may react with semiconductor surfaces to form a compound with new electronic properties.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] A contamination layer at the interface may effectively widen the barrier.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] The surface of the semiconductor may reconstruct leading to a new electronic state.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] The dependence of contact resistance on the details of the interfacial chemistry is what makes the reproducible fabrication of ohmic contacts such a manufacturing challenge.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] The fabrication of the ohmic contacts is a much-studied part of materials engineering that nonetheless remains something of an art.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] The reproducible, reliable fabrication of contacts relies on extreme cleanliness of the semiconductor surface.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Since a *native oxide* rapidly forms on the surface of silicon, for example, the performance of a contact can depend sensitively on the details of preparation.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Often the contact region is heavily doped to ensure the type of contact wanted.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] As a rule, ohmic contacts on semiconductors form more easily when the semiconductor is highly doped near the junction; a high doping narrows the depletion region at the interface and allow electrons to flow in both directions easily at any bias by tunneling through the barrier.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] The fundamental steps in contact fabrication are semiconductor surface cleaning, contact metal deposition, patterning and annealing.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Surface cleaning may be performed by sputter-etching, chemical etching, reactive gas etching or ion milling.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] For example, the native oxide of silicon may be removed with a hydrofluoric acid dip, while GaAs is more typically cleaned by a bromine-methanol dip.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] After cleaning, metals are deposited via sputter deposition, evaporation or chemical vapor deposition (CVD).
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Sputtering is a faster and more convenient method of metal deposition than evaporation but the ion bombardment from the plasma may induce surface states or even invert the charge carrier type at the surface.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] For this reason the gentler but still rapid CVD may be used.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Post-deposition annealing of contacts is useful for relieving stress as well as for inducing any desirable reactions between the metal and the semiconductor.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Because deposited metals can themselves react in ambient conditions, to the detriment of the contacts' electrical properties, it is common to form ohmic contacts with layered structures, with the bottom layer, in contact with the semiconductor, chosen for its ability to induce ohmic behaviour.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] A diffusion barrier-layer may be used to prevent the layers from mixing during any annealing process.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] The measurement of contact resistance is most simply performed using a four-point probe although for more accurate determination, use of the transmission line method is typical.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Aluminum was originally the most important contact metal for silicon which was used with either the n-type or p-type semiconductor.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] As with other reactive metals, Al contributes to contact formation by consuming oxygen from native silicon-dioxide residue.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Pure aluminum did react with the silicon, so it was replaced by silicon-doped aluminum and eventually by silicides less prone to diffuse during subsequent high-temperature processing.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Modern ohmic contacts to silicon such as titanium-tungsten disilicide are usually silicides made by CVD.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Contacts are often made by depositing the transition metal and forming the silicide by annealing with the result that the silicide may be non-stoichiometric.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Silicide contacts can also be deposited by direct sputtering of the compound or by ion implantation of the transition metal followed by annealing.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Formation of contacts to compound semiconductors is considerably more difficult than with silicon.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] For example, GaAs surfaces tend to lose arsenic and the trend towards As loss can be considerably exacerbated by the deposition of metal.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] In addition, the volatility of As limits the amount of post-deposition annealing that GaAs devices will tolerate.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] One solution for GaAs and other compound semiconductors is to deposit a low-bandgap alloy contact layer as opposed to a heavily doped layer.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] For example, GaAs itself has a smaller bandgap than AlGaAs and so a layer of GaAs near its surface can promote ohmic behavior.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] In general the technology of ohmic contacts for III-V and II-VI semiconductors is much less developed than for Si.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Transparent or semi-transparent contacts are necessary for active matrix LCDs, optoelectronic devices such as laser diodes and photovoltaics.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] The most popular choice is indium tin oxide, a metal that is formed by reactive sputtering of an In-Sn target in an oxide atmosphere.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] The RC time constant associated with contact resistance can limit the frequency response of devices.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] The charging and discharging of the leads resistance is a major cause of power dissipation in high-clock-rate digital electronics.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Contact resistance causes power dissipation by Joule heating in low-frequency and analog circuits (for example, solar cells) made from less common semiconductors.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] The establishment of a contact fabrication methodology is a critical part of the technological development of any new semiconductor.
[src:esd-protection/ohmic-contact] Electromigration and delamination at contacts are also a limitation on the lifetime of electronic devices.
[src:esd-protection/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] A **transient-voltage-suppression** (**TVS**) **diode**, also **transil**, **transorb** or **thyrector**, is an electronic component used to protect electronics from voltage spikes induced on connected wires.
[src:esd-protection/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] The device operates by shunting excess current when the induced voltage exceeds the avalanche breakdown potential.
[src:esd-protection/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] It is a clamping device, suppressing all overvoltages above its breakdown voltage.
[src:esd-protection/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] It automatically resets when the overvoltage goes away, but absorbs much more of the transient energy internally than a similarly rated crowbar device.
[src:esd-protection/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] A transient-voltage-suppression diode may be either unidirectional or bidirectional.
[src:esd-protection/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] A unidirectional device operates as a rectifier in the forward direction like any other avalanche diode, but is made and tested to handle very large peak currents.
[src:esd-protection/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] A bidirectional transient-voltage-suppression diode can be represented by two mutually opposing avalanche diodes in series with one another and connected in parallel with the circuit to be protected.
[src:esd-protection/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] While this representation is schematically accurate, physically the devices are now manufactured as a single component.
[src:esd-protection/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] A transient-voltage-suppression diode can respond to over-voltages faster than other common over-voltage protection components such as varistors or gas discharge tubes.
[src:esd-protection/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] The actual clamping occurs in roughly one picosecond, but in a practical circuit the inductance of the wires leading to the device imposes a higher limit.
[src:esd-protection/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] This makes transient-voltage-suppression diodes useful for protection against very fast and often damaging voltage transients.
[src:esd-protection/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] These fast over-voltage transients are present on all distribution networks and can be caused by either internal or external events, such as lightning or motor arcing.
[src:esd-protection/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] Transient voltage suppressors will fail if they are subjected to voltages or conditions beyond those that the particular product was designed to accommodate.
[src:esd-protection/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] There are three key modes in which the TVS will fail: short, open, and degraded device.
[src:esd-protection/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] TVS diodes are sometimes referred to as transorbs, from the Vishay trademark *TransZorb*.
